column18:
A lot of the terms depended on context. Some were not specific enough: keeping a lost wallet is not immoral if there is no contact information inside it. Others were concepts that could not be classified as moral or immoral, or as pleasant or unpleasant because they had too many layers: virginity as a concept falls in different categories than virginity as a truth. Being a virgin is not unpleasant, but the construct of virginity is. Moreover, being a virgin is not immoral, but to label it moral would be to suggest that the alternative is not.

There were many things I did not think were immoral, but did think were despicable, unpleasant, or bad. But I suppose that's the point. I just wonder if people are really able to make accurate moral judgments so quickly for some of these words.

column21:
A major problem was that when I accidentally answered one wrong because I was moving too quickly, I took far longer than normal to answer the next one. I understand that this will be controlled for, and I understand that my accidentally labeling "homosexuals" as unpleasant, for example, will not contribute to general data on how humans feel about things, so I will not be ever so slightly skewing things, I do feel that this clouded up the data for this particular experiment. I find this a problem with every reaction time task I've ever done, and I hope that not everyone has such difficulty (though I'm sure the volume of misplaced responses on my part is being greatly overestimated).

This is a very interesting task. Were it not being timed, I think others should do it to get an improved self-perception of their political leanings.

"Hitler" made me question the uniformity of the words. A single proper noun does not belong here.

column18:
Some words created a conflict in my mind, as you could argue either side. Something like assisted suicide is unpleasant if it's a friend or family member who's going to die; however, assisted suicide can be thought of as pleasant as it ends a patient's suffering. It's hard to respond quickly when a term is so loaded, and if you do respond quickly, it's easy to regret your answer and want to change it.
Other ambiguous terms that can be argued as both pleasant and unpleasant or moral and immoral:
alcohol
marijuana
police
military
conservative
liberal
column21:
It's very hard to focus on the words for extended periods of time. Sometimes I'd be a bit distracted and not fully think about the term I'm responding to. I think shorter bursts of terms and longer spaces between terms would help remedy this. Also, the red exclamation mark definitely makes you panic a bit if you've gotten distracted, haven't really thought about the term and suddenly have to answer. The speed of the terms and the red exclamation mark led to some of my answers not reflecting my actual feelings about the term.

Also, I found myself grouping both moral/pleasant and immoral/unpleasant together into just "good" and "bad" connotations due to the speed of the task (i.e. I didn't make a distinction between moral and pleasant). Often, I'd inadvertently just default to how society portrays the terms rather than considering my own feelings about it. For instance, I have no problem with premarital sex, but that term carries a negative connotation, especially in the media, which influenced my answer.
